I sent an email to bylaw officer James Whalen to acknowledge the receipt. Asked for pictoral evidence of the notice and site location/address that complainant may have submitted to them. He didn't have any location information.

I spoke on the phone (about 45 minutes) with complainant Myson Effa regarding his complaint. He seems to have general concerns about the use of glyphosate product likely based on prevailing perception of Roundup, and didn't want SSISC or anyone else to use glyphosate herbicides in the area. He also mentioned that SSISC didn't provide him and the community an advance notice of pesticide use. His own property is not infested with Japanese Knotweed and therefore is not being treated.

I will conduct an inspection of SSISC treatment notification practices.

Spoke with complainant, David (604-230-7143) to conduct the preliminary assessment of the complaint and ask if he has any additional info. David indicated that Mann Blueberry Estate (4635 88 St Delta; phone 778 549 6851) allegedly sprayed "Round up" in front of their own house which is city's property. Tried calling the alleged offender but no answer. Will try to contact them again.
Got hold of farmer (Sukh Brar) on May 26 who said that they did not spray and refused to participate in this assessment. He also provided his mother's phone number but requested not to call her as he said that he will ask her not to participate in this assessment (Balwinder- 778 233-8702).

No conclusive evidence to prove who applied herbicide and what was applied.

Referred the matter back to the City of Delta. Spoke with Kevin Li at the City and updated him about my preliminary assessment and refusal of the farmer to participate. Kevin will inform us if City has a pesticide bylaw that has been contravened and under which they are going to pursue action then send me their action plan & I will let them know how we might be able to support them.

The City issued a warning letter on May 27th (attached). No further action required from us.

Inspection Summary:
P:\WANSHARE\ROB\Compliance\Complaints 25600-05\! Inbox ORIGINAL\2020

Spoke with Alison to discuss the complaint and get any additional info. She does not have name and contact number of the alleged offender. I advised her to call Township of Langley. Also educated her about the IPM compliance process regarding Round Up and other herbicides use in this situation (see below). She is going to contact Township and did not have any further concerns for us to follow up.

The Integrated Pest Management Act (IPMA) regulates the sale and application of pesticides in British Columbia. Under the IPMA, the use of Round Up by both commercial pest removal companies and residents requires either a pesticide license or Residential Applicator Certificate (RAC). While an RAC is required under the IPMA, the majority of residents who apply this pesticide do not hold this certificate and it is beyond the scope of government resources to pursue all unauthorized uses.  

Some individual municipalities have bylaws around pesticide application which may be applicable to your complaint. Go to https://mytrainingbc.ca/homepesticideuse/section1-1b.html to find links to pesticide bylaws in communities around the province.

I looked into this place more and talked with the COM finally. It seems like this guy is storing cars that he picks up using his towing business and pulling certain parts from the cars that are at the property, but they are not dismantling the whole car like a shop would. No doubt he isnt dismantling properly, but when I looked at WDR I forgot that VDRIP has that home-based business exemption. I checked in with Ross since he had one similar one, and agreed that this situation lines up with that  

If he lives on/owns the property and is operating his business at this location, would this exempt the operations from WDR as it is a home-based business? 

"vehicle dismantling and recycling industry" means establishments, except home-based businesses, educational facilities and establishments of hobbyists or artisans, engaged in wrecking or dismantling vehicles or in recycling or disposing of parts and other waste material from vehicles 

Wanted to get your thoughts before moving forward

Inspection Summary:
Placing rodenticide bait in an inaccessible area (e.g. wall void, etc.) is not a compliance issue as it's permitted by the product label. It could not be determined who placed the rodenticide in the ceiling panel and who pried open the hatch in question. Strata representatives (Rob Hamill and Kayla Hamill) reported that "the strata does not handle any poison what so ever". A general response was issued to the strata providing tips on best practices to avoid similar situations.

Here's the email received from Assured Pest Management:

"Our technician visited the site yesterday (January 7, 2020) afternoon. 
Her report follows: Inspected several ceiling hatches on the first floor- in front of 108, between 116 and the fire door, (the hatch in question), between units 111 and 110, between units 115 and 114 and just before the fire door beside unit 110. No bait found visible in any. The hatch between 116 and the fire door has been affixed with new screws (photo below). Mouse droppings found visible in several of them along with holes and runways in the insulation and should be properly baited in the near future, (see report from September 27). Inspected all other ceiling hatches and found no apparent issue. Inspected accessible equipment on site (exterior bait stations) and found no issue.

The broken/bent ceiling hatch in question had already been repaired, the hallway cleaned and the contrac pack removed- we don't know who did this or when.

What we know- we applied baits to ceiling voids in this building back in September, using contrac meal packs with PCP#30140. The first floor ceiling hatches dont have proper hinged covers with a lock, just hatch plates screwed into the ceiling. We only baited one hatch on the first floor because most of the hatches has multiple screws, many of which were painted over- this was a multi screw hatch as well, and she doesnt remember if it was this one or a different one that she baited back in September. The building had an active mouse problem then and continues to have rodent activity in various areas. We have serviced this property each month since September and there has been no issue with exposed baits or tampered with stations or hatches. 

We dont know who pried open the hatch in question, when they did it, why they did it, and if any bait actually spilled out or not. We just know that someone did this and left the bait bag sitting on the hatch and stuff on the floor (as reported by the resident). In the pictures sent there is no bait spilled on the hallway floor, only bits of ceiling. In the picture the bait bag is chewed into, but we dont know if it was empty or not.

We also know that whoever did the hatch prying was not a responsible individual- I would think a legitimate contractor accessing a utility hatch for a legitimate reason would clean up whatever fell out, and if they had accidentally bent the hatch that they would fix it, and re-attach it.  So it seems likely that the hatch was tampered with- maybe by the people in the building who were doing illegal pest control there before, maybe by someone in a dispute with strata, maybe just by a kid jumping up at the ceiling, we just dont know.

Brett Johnston 
604-463-0007 
www.assuredenvironmental.ca

Inspection Summary:
Call Back Details:
Reports of suspected pesticide poisoning should be reported to IPMcomplaints@gov.bc.ca with all relevant data about evidence and observations.  Requested pertinent info about the incident about which she called to skip that step.

Requested details of incident:
What happened:  Blood-work on cat indicated delayed coagulation consistent with secondary poisoning.
Date and time: October 13, 2019 
Location: 4749 Fairbridge Dr. Duncan, BC V9L 6N8
Alleged contravener: neighbour indicated that their pest control company said they use Bromadialone. It was relayed to her that the pest control company had said that someone in the area may have been using rodenticides inappropriately. The pest control company alleged that Buckerfield's sells commercial rodenticides to homeowners without verifying that the intended user is a PCO or farmer.  (Abell Pest Control called on October 15, 2019 with such a complaint, see https://a100.gov.bc.ca/int/cvis/nris/nris.html?fromRoleSelect=true#/complaint/140748;  Inspection of October 22, 2019 found Duncan Buckerfield's out of compliance with requirement to ensure pesticide was appropriate for intended use, see https://a100.gov.bc.ca/int/cvis/nris/nris.html?fromRoleSelect=true#/inspection/141008 [in preparation])

In Canada, rodenticides are regulated by both federal and provincial legislation.  

Under federal regulations, since January 1, 2013, use restrictions for several commercial class rodenticides came into effect on product labels approved by Health Canada. These restrictions are intended to prevent the accidental exposure of children and non-target animals. Anticoagulant rodenticides, of the type you describe, must now either be placed in tamper-resistant bait stations or in locations not accessible to children, pets, livestock and non-target wildlife. Such commercial rodenticide baits are now labelled for use only by certified pest control operators, farmers and persons authorized in government-approved pest control programs.  

In addition, the BC Integrated Pest Management Regulation, as of July 1, 2016 requires that pesticide vendors must refuse sales of pesticides if a customer does not provide sufficient information to confirm that the pesticide is appropriate for the intended use.  The Ministry is currently conducting a review of commercial vendors to ensure, amongst other things, compliance with this requirement.  That focus will help ensure that commercial rodenticides are sold only to persons trained to use them with the intention of avoiding secondary poisoning of non-target animals such as pets.

Further guidance on dealing with pesticide emergencies is available at https://www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/industry/agriculture-seafood/animals-and-crops/plant-health/pesticides-agriculture/pesticide-emergencies/pesticide-poisoning

Inspection Summary:
P:\WANSHARE\ROB\Compliance\Complaints 25600-05\133942 Silverton Creek

On 2019-08-21, I attended Silverton to look at the algae in the creek, determine if there was an obvious source of nutrients causing the algae and also, potentially, sample the algae and water.

I walked along the creek upstream from the bridge, then from the bridge downstream until my access was limited.  I then walked along the beach to the mouth of the creek.  I noted dead algae on rocks in some locations, but very limited amounts.  I found a very small amount of live algae just before the mouth of the creek.  The live algae were smaller than a dinner plate and on a couple of rocks.  

I determined that water samples wouldnt be appropriate as the algae was no longer widespread, so the change in water chemistry was likely no longer affected.

I took two samples of algae for review.

Dennis Einarson, an Impact Assessment Biologist, identified the genus of algae as Ulothrix.  He provided me with a basic outline of the algae, stating its common in cool fast flowing streams at the time when groundwater becomes the major component of the stream volume and as per Wikipedia:

Ulothrix is a genus of filamentous green algae, generally found in fresh and marine water. Its cells are normally as broad as they are long, and they thrive in the low temperatures of spring and winter. They become attached to surfaces by a modified holdfast cell. 

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulothrix

Further information can be found at:

https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Taxonomy/Browser/wwwtax.cgi?mode=Tree&id=43940&lvl=3&keep=1&srchmode=1&unlock

The algal type is not of concern in the environment, and the growth has subsequently ceased.

Location Description: Dollar Tree, Duncan Plaza, 10-360 Trunk Rd #12, Duncan, BC V9L 2P6
Inspection Summary:
In a phone call of March 4, 2019 assistant store manager Pat Egan confirmed that rodenticide bait stations (Tomcat Mouse Killer, PCP 30757, bromethalin) were displayed on open access shelf areas at the Dollar Tree outlet at Duncan Plaza, 10-360 Trunk Rd #12, Duncan, BC V9L 2P6

The Integrated Pest Management Regulation (IPMR, http://www.bclaws.ca/EPLibraries/bclaws_new/document/ID/freeside/604_2004) requires that such pesticides be sold only if the business holds a valid Pesticide Vendors Licence and that dispensing staff hold Pesticide Dispenser certificates.  

In addition, non-Excluded pesticides must be stored in a manner that prevents the public from accessing the pesticides without the assistance of a certified dispenser.

When the above was explained to Ms. Egan, she committed to removing the Tomcat bait stations from the sales area.

Dear Rene,

Thank you for your message from January 25, 2019 regarding your concerns with the use of pesticides, specifically regarding Round-up, in British Columbia. I appreciate your concern to protect human health and the environment.

In Canada, pesticides are regulated federally by Health Canada's Pest Management Regulatory Agency (PMRA), and provincially by the Ministry of Environment & Climate Change Strategy. Pesticides can only be used in Canada if they have been evaluated and registered by the PMRA, who impose conditions and limitations for each pesticide use. We rely on the expertise of PMRA's scientists to conduct health and environmental reviews to ensure that pesticides allowed for use in Canada will not cause unacceptable risk to people and the environment when used according to label directions. In BC, my Ministry administers the Integrated Pest Management Act (IPMA), which regulates the sale and use of pesticides and requires the use of Integrated Pest Management (IPM) when applying pesticides in the province. IPM involves steps for pest prevention, pest monitoring to identify treatment thresholds, and using alternatives to pesticides where possible. 

Your specific municipality may also have bylaws that restrict the use of certain pesticides on landscaped areas. 

Thank you again for your interest in protecting the environment and for taking the time to share your comments.



Robert Au, M.Sc., P.Ag.
Senior IPM Officer
Ministry of Environment and Climate Change Strategy
Suite 200  10470 152 Street, Surrey BC  V3R 0Y3

Phone: 604 582-5214
www.gov.bc.ca/PestManagement

Inspection Summary:
I spoke to the complainant, Andrew on the phone (604-600-6973) on December 17, 2018. After checking in CRISP, I confirmed to him that the applicator was certified and had a valid pesticide use licence. He also wanted to know if a "fumigation management plan" was submitted to the Ministry prior to treatment in his suite. After looking into the pesticide use record that Licensee provided, I told the complainant that PCO did not fumigate their suite. Instead the PCO used fogging method, which does not require an FMP. I asked if he received a Treatment Notice prior to the pesticide application. He said that he received notice via Email which he forwarded to me. The treatment notice had the preparation instructions and evacuation time, but did not list the name(s) and PCP number(s) of the pesticides to be used. 

I spoke with Andrew on December 19 again, as he wanted to know the names of chemicals that were used in his suite. After looking into the pesticide use record that Licensee provided, I told Andrew the names of the four chemicals that were used. The complainant understood and did not have any further questions.

I sent an email to the Licensee (licence # 23371, valid until April 1, 2019) on December 17, 2018 requesting a copy of the Treatment Notice that he gave to the complainant. Mr. Fang responded on December 18 and provided me a copy of the notice and screenshot of the text message that he sent to the complainant indicating the time to re-enter (see attached document). 2018-12-10 - EPO Blake contacted Billy Doorn of Mountain View Electric regarding the situation.  Billy explained that the river bank adjacent to the farm buildings, specifically manure storage, had been eroding for some time.  The property owner had applied to FLNROD to undertake remedial works on the banks, and hired Mountain View Electric.  EPO Blake informed Billy of the AWCR and the requirements for manure storage facilities to have setbacks from waterways and drinking water sources.  Billy stated that the erosion wasn't a current concern but the property wanted to remediate the banks before it became a concern.
EPO Blake then spoke to Jason Marzinzik, Water Stewardship Officer FLNROD.  EPO Blake explained that the Billy had stated that the concern was not current, but for the future.  WSO Marzinzik stated that the application for works would require an P.Eng report and EPO Blake stated that this report would highlight any concerns which would be in ENV jurisdiction.

Mr. Gerler has a water licence (C03594, client ID 071549) to draw water from Laughlin Creek which is adjacent to where the spraying occurred.  He is concerned that it will impact his drinking water, and the fish and wildlife (elk) that are around the creek.  His friend (Phil Coward) was staying at his house and witnessed the spraying.  Mr. Gerler called when he returned and saw the posted treatment notice sign.

I spoke with Crystal Chadburn of MOTI who sent the treatment records for the site (October 10, 2018).  Wells are identified prior to treatments, but the water licence layer in iMap is not typically used, so it was unknown to the contractor that this property had a water intake from the creek.  

MOTI contractor followed up with a site visit with the complainant.  Clarification was made on where treatments actually occurred (only knotweed), and that contamination of water would have been unlikely due to dry conditions, low mobility in soil and selective application methods.  An agreement was made with Mr. Gerler not to treat the knotweed near his property.  It was difficult to obtain an accurate measurement between the water intake line (also difficult to identify which line was the active line) and the treatment area, but was around the 30m mark.  

MOTI outlined actions to be taken moving forward including ensuring applicators turn on water licence layers in addition to well layers in iMap, and checking with home owners prior to treatment, as well as ensuring that applicators record reasons for reducing NTZ around wells/water intake when applicable (as required under 35 (1) (I).

Inspection Summary: P:\WANSHARE\ROB\Authorizations 10400-60\105178 Delfresh Mushroom Farm Ltd. MCFR

Ongoing for years issue with neighbouring property for years.  Dan own's an acre of residential property, farmer kitty-corner grows berries of some kind.  A couple of years ago, he noticed a bad smell from the sprays at this farm.  After some digging he discovered that they were spraying malathion with an air-blaster.  Dan believes he read that this product should not be sprayed with an air-blast sprayer when children can be exposed (there is a church across the street that runs youth programs and a corner store across the street which sells ice cream/has outside tables).  Dan spoke with owner of Arjuna Farms to go over his concerns/ask that he stop spraying this product.  Dan has 15' cedars around the property but says the spray is still coming over them.

On August 9th, Dan was in his pool and could feel/smell the spray.  He went over to the farm and saw a 30' cloud of spray from the air-blast sprayer.  He stopped the sprayer operator who didn't know what he was spraying.  Dan told him to stop spraying or he would call the cops.  The farm owner took over spraying and a confrontation happened between Dan and the owner.  Dan received spray in his face and called 911.  The ambulance came, and the Abbotsford Police came and opened a file.  The police went and spoke with the owner.

Dan also called the city about his concerns and was told to call Ministry of Agriculture.  He called and spoke with Regional Agrologist, Kim Sutherthand but wasn't happy with their answer.  According to Kim Sutherland, the farmer has been inspected & is within the farming guidelines.  Their airblast sprayer is calibrated at the beginning and end of every season.

He said he has videos of the spray clouds, which I asked him to sent to me.

Additional Comments: White Star has had a ticket issued by a CO for improper pesticide storage. Chelsea also did an inspection and notified the manager that they needed an Industrial Vegetation licence to do that type of work. Mr. Murray Krangle was the initial complainant who made to the report to the city and lives next to the creek.
Inspection Summary:
I called and left a message for Erin Gorby on July 26 2018.

Aug.1 2018: Erin received information from both by their service contractor (White Star Property Service 3294 (604) 882-0075) & resident who made a compliant to the City of Maple Ridge. After they applied the pesticide, the contractor noticed that they had sprayed knotweed, heard a dog barking in nearby house to keep dog out of area, as they were walking to investigate they noticed that there was water in a ditch. The resident nearby the application was upset that contractor sprayed knotweed. Erin took pictures of signage, knotweed patch and ditch 3-4 days afterward. The knotweed may have been growing right out of the bank beside the ditch.
I spoke to Ashley Hill, Business Development Manager at White Star. Both White Star and the City of Maple Ridge were aware of the contravention; application to knotweed < 1m of high water mark. Erin has stopped spray program until White Star can change their protocol to do initial ground truthing.

Contacted White Star on Aug. 3 2018. Ashley Hill indicated that the applicator called city to double check area prior to the application and that the drainage creek was not observed due to thick vegetation. 

On Aug. 8 2018, I spoke with Erin to notify her of my compliance determination based on the available information I had. I let her know of White Star's non-compliances (Incorrect licence category, application of pesticide <1m of the high water mark) and that a Warning letter was issued to the company on the same day. Erin was satisfied with my response and action.

Inspection Summary:
I called Peter on July 16 2018 and left a message. Pesticide sprayed by Green Admiral Nature Restoration licence 22229 contracted by Richmond on July 20 2018 at 6700 NUMBER 7 ROAD, RICHMOND.

I talked to Peter on July 30th after having received photos he sent me from Alon of the notification signs. Green Admiral received an Advisory for non-compliance of the full requirements of their treatment notification. Peter seemed satisfied with my response and inquired whether the pesticide complaint from Alon was in fact a valid health concern. I let him know that spot application results in minimal spray drift and usually does not contaminate ground water due to the small amount of pesticide used.

Additional Comments:
Related to complaint 94320. A 1'x1' sign is 929 cm2 and satisfies the outdoor size requirement for the purposes of IPM Regulation 63(1).
He contacted the City. They spot sprayed with wicks, 1 m from ditch with systemic pesticide.

along Number 7 road beside and in front of the callers
property
Inspection Summary:
Pesticide sprayed by Green Admiral Nature Restoration on July 20 2018 at 6700 NUMBER 7 ROAD, RICHMOND.
I spoke to Alon on July 26 2018. He was happy with the details I provided and understood that the contractor for Richmond was in compliance with the regulations except for signage. Alon was reasonable satisfied that City was following all rules applicable when they were applying Roundup. Alon was concerned about fish contamination, groundwater and his organic farm nearby.

I phoned Alon on July 30th after having received photos he took of the notification signs. I mentioned that I'd be sending out a letter to the Green Admiral licence 22229 indicating that they must comply with the full requirements of treatment notification signs.

Additional Comments: Diane is the neighbor across the street to the farm where the alleged incident occurred. I phoned Diane and left a voice message with contact information on July 24 2018. Diane phoned me back on July 24 2018.
Inspection Summary:
Incident occurred on Saturday July 21, 2018 at approximately 2:30 pm when wind speed was about 17 km/hr. There was the smell of the pesticides being applied. I checked CRISP to see if Sidhu Blueberry Farms (across the street from Diane) was licenced, they are not. Diane indicated that this farm typically applies pesticides by boom about 4x per year.

As the alleged pesticide spraying relates to agriculture, the use requirements that restrict licensee and confirmation holders to pesticide application of 8 km/hr or less outdoors does not apply since many farmers are not regulated under the IPM Act. However, I relayed to Diane the farmer is lawfully bound to apply the pesticides according to the pesticide label. I asked that her contact me with further information if acquired.

Additional Comments:
-	Bob Lassam lives in Keremeos and has complained numerous times to ministry pesticide officers about illegal pesticide use in the last several years, especially the use of Roundup.  He first called the ministry this year on March 19th, asking to have Roundup removed from stores in the area.  I left a voicemail for him as a response to his complaint but did not hear back right away.

-	Mr. Lassam did call me back on July 5th of this year.  The conversation was quite disjointed, as he seemed agitated but also confused about the rules around pesticide use.  He was also verbally abusive and used profanities.  It seems that the root of the issue is that he lost his wife to cancer and feels that the Roundup is the cause of that.  The pesticide uses he is describing are all legal and being carried out by municipalities with valid authorizations.

-	I believe both the Conservation Officer Service and the RCMP have interacted with this individual as well in the last couple of years as a result of complaints he has made about pesticide use.

Summary of email sent to Mr. Limpright: 

Good Afternoon Mr. Limpright,

Thank you for your email below regarding Delfresh Mushroom Farm Ltd. I understand that odour still remains as a large concern, and the Ministry of Environment and Climate Change Strategy (Ministry) continues to move forward with compliance with the Mushroom Composting Regulation.

As you mention below, the Ministry conducted an inspection of the Delfresh Mushrooms composting facility on May 29, 2018. The facility was issued a warning as it was found to be out of compliance for uncovered goody water, uncovered straw pre-wetting dunk tank, and two administrative issues. As a result of this warning, this facility is scheduled for a follow up inspection.  Continued non-compliance will result in an escalating compliance response consistent with the Ministrys  Compliance and Enforcement Policy and Procedure. This could result in prosecution, the assignment of an administrative monetary penalty or other enforcement actions.

Thank you for taking the time to write.

NOTES FROM CO MYRONIUK: 

2018-06-04 - 1015 hrs - CO Myroniuk called and spoke with COM.  COM stated that he called RAPP line on/around May 4th.  CO Myroniuk queried ECC database and ERS records and could not locate an ERS, therefore, the initial report may have been routed to FLNRO, C&E.
COM stated that the issue is regarding management and storage of manure on a large, commercial feedlot. The water body is likely an ephemeral stream, however, the concern is that the location of the manure storage is in the middle of the creek and often fills it.  Interior Health has been on site and has encouraged COM to report to RAPP.  CO advised that he would refer the matter to MOE - Environmental Protection Division.

2018-06-07 Call with John Nurkoswki
Flows year round, but quickly in the springtime 20L / second, more than a trickle. Spring fed and a drinking water source (above) - 1940s concrete culvert. 1990s or 2000s the area was backfilled over the stream and put in a feedlot. Backs up onto neighbours land, and the cattle walk around it. Neighbour to the south west has stream water flow going through the site, Longhorn Feedlots. John sent email to M Murphy showcasing the change in the stream from 1959 to 2000s.

2018-08-14 Call with John Nurkoski
Called to inform M Murphy that the site is currently dry, but in the springtime it is a bad location, especially as people use  this spring as a drinking water source. He suggested that M Murphy contact Brian Lorde of IHA, as he had conducted an inspection of the site and had completed an internal report.

2018-08-21 Email with Greg Baytalan
History of non-compliance with FIRB, IHA has information he can provide regarding the Marshall Feedlot in Kelowna. A follow up conversation to occur.

Location Description: Pauline Johnson Elementary School on 22nd Street
Inspection Summary: Rosemary is concerned that the dolomitic lime is getting onto balconies and where children are running through. I phoned her on May 25 and informed her that the use of fertilizers (lime & potash) are not regulated by BC Ministry of Environment. Lime is often used to adjust the pH pending results from soil samples and potash is potassium, a major nutrient required by plants. I recommended her to contact the Parks and recreation dept. for West Vancouver and speak with a foreman in charge of that area. Rosemary thanked me for the information and the call back.

Additional Comments: Received in my NRIS Dashboard May 23 2018.
Location Description: At Alderview townhouse complex - 27411 28th Avenue in Aldergrove - near Bertrand Creek.
Inspection Summary:
Yard Pro Custom Landscaping is alleged to have sprayed on the edge of the creek. Chris has a valid landscape certificate 202585 but I was unable to locate a licence associated with Yard Pro. I contacted Chris Penner of Yard Pro Custom Landscaping ((604) 807-9020) and left a message on May 25. Chris called me back the same day and let me know that pesticide application was for clover. There is a greenbelt between the lawn and creek of about 30 feet which he felt was an adequate buffer. 

Offering a service of a pesticide application for a fee requires a pesticide service licence. I contacted Chris Penner of Yard Pro to inquire whether he has a licence. He said he will email me the licence when he finds it. In an email to me Chris indicated that he had applied for a licence prior to the application but did not receive a response as the person processing licences was on vacation. Since Gayla was on annual leave around that time, it may well have been that Chris applied for a licence in advance of the application. Alleged violation date is May 16 2018. Yard Pro obtained a pesticide user licence 25037 on June 14 2018.

2018-04-23 Dan Bings requested I do not attend site, this is a non issue
2018-05-02 Called COM
Inspection Summary:
2018-05-02 Phone call with Mr. Walker 2:30pm - 3:30pm
Surface water and ground water - concerned mostly because of drinking water and also animals accessing the water. He has had a problem with one of his cows, and the vet stated that it is known that upper respiratory come with biosolids depending on how it leaches into the water. Many drinking wells are rising (in water level). Creek is running at four feet, appears that he is placing materials about four feet at the creek. Springtime there is a 50% snow (water) increase, which makes contact with the biosolids and then discharges into the creek below. He states that his cows that access the creek water for drinking have recently gotten upper respiratory illness, which has never happened in the past. He thinks that the cause of the illness is due to the biosolids. He mentioned that he uses the creek often for his cattle, and he doesn't believe the Ministry has done enough to protect the watercourse. He has stated that he doesn't believe that the site is being managed properly, or that the Ministry put enough thought into the risks associated with the site. Officer Murphy stated that the site has been reviewed through the application process, that Authorizations staff went to site prior to waste being discharged, and a QP has been hired by the owner to check on the water quality parameters. The Ministry will be keeping a close eye on what happens with the site, but so far there are no issues with water quality.
Other issues discussed:
WSA s.11 issues -  concerned that he isn't able to access over his bridge / put the rocks in the stream
City of Kelowna closure of Barnhartvale landfill - concerned about lack of access to waste disposal / litter issues
We also talked about Ontario, because we both used to live there
We chatted about the RAPP line and how the call came to the Compliance department / Vernon is the closest location for triaging the call.

Ms. Dangelmaier also informed Officer Kurinka that Domtar has received a number of complaints from the public this morning at the downtown AQ monitoring station was reading TRS 19.2 ppb @ 09:32.

2018-04-27 Phone call
The COM has friends that live on Curtis Rd. Water table is rising due to the landfill raising the grade of the site (added pressure from waste). The problem is changing the underground water flow, the site used to be sand / silty clay layer above the aquifer. Water naturally comes up from the naural spring below (3-5ft). Robert Lake drains naturally betwee the ponds (generally is empty in July due to evaporation). The change in water (hydraulically) is causing erosion of the street. Pumping between al three ponds - Robert Lake via underground pipes. The whole slope beside the lake (Slough Pond?) is contaminated. The City has dug trenches for gas processing, but the ditching has caused water to pond onto neighbouring farm. Robert Lake is an endangered habitat, so by changing in the water volume, you are changing the endangered habitat. The landfill has changed the natural habitat / hydrology as most of the refuse is found in the ponds. They are pumping out 400gal/min to Okanagan Lake, and pumping in 200-300gal/min into the landfill ponds. However, despite the high inflow, the water level does not appear to be decreasing. If this is happening on a regular basis, the change in water volume will affect the water chemistry - affect waters that are receiving the water waste. Running through 6-8inch pipes - pumping the ditches. There is a lot more than just ppm being affected, so COM wasn't sure about other parameters but temperatures / pH / turbidity should be looked into. The neighbours are now starting to experience the water issues, and they are $50,000. The sewer line on the road (dirty lines) connect to ponds?....The City claims that the pond water is clean enough to discharge to the Lake. Contact Paul Warnock, resident of Curtis Rd, if you need more information 250-212-7474.

Additional Comments: Jim Barr believes that wildlife such as squirrels and owls are consuming bait from rodenticide bait boxes which have been recently deployed around buildings located on Savory Island, BC. I responded to his complaint on April 27, 2018 by ensuring that I had relevant info and specifics such as the PCO that deployed the bait stations. I emailed Jim additional info regarding rodenticide bait station requirements and the ministry's certification requirement for staff working under licenced PCOs in BC. Jim believes that the island has seen an explosion of anti-coagulant rodenticide use over the past year which has contributed to death of wildlife. I let him know that not all bait stations contain anti-coagulant rodenticides - some hold mechanical traps while others may also include low toxicity rodenticides such as corn cellulose. Further, bait stations are only designed to allow target rodents entry and are held to requirements that reduce the risk of non-target exposure. Health Canada also evaluates and registers all pesticides that are legal to be used in Canada.

Inspection Summary:
Bait MUST be placed either in tamper-resistant bait stations or in locations not accessible to children, pets, livestock or non-target wildlife&
Bait stations (tier 3) used for the placement of rodenticide bait indoors, in locations not accessible to pets or livestock must have the following characteristics: (1) be constructed of high-strength material (e.g., metal or injection molded plastic) and resistant to destruction by children: (2) have an entrance designed so that children cannot reach the bait; (3) have internal structure which prevents bait from being shaken loose; (4) have an access panel that fastens securely and locks (e.g., metal screw or padlock); and (5) bear the product name, active ingredient, guarantee, registration number, WARNING POISON, and the skull and crossbones symbol. Bait stations (tier 2) used for the placement of rodenticide bait indoors, in locations accessible to pets or livestock must have the following characteristics, in addition to those outlined above for tier 3 bait stations: (1) resistant to destruction by non-target animals; and (2) have an entrance designed so that non-target animals cannot reach bait. Bait applied outdoors and above-ground MUST be placed in bait stations. Bait stations (tier 1) used outdoors, above-ground, in locations accessible to children, pets and non-target wildlife must have the following characteristics, in addition to those outlined above for tier 2 and 3 bait stations: (1) be resistant to destruction or weakening by elements of typical non-catastrophic weather (such as, snow, rain, extremes of temperature and humidity, direct sunshine, etc.).

2018-04-11 update from Ashley Robertson:

On April 10, 2018 members of the Canadian Coast Guard and Ministry of Environment Emergency Response conducted a site assessment at the above location. The following are results of the on-water and on-land assessment: 
- Primary concern: Observed runoff entering the marine environment from the site. The biodegradation of wood chips on-site and pooling water is contributing to sheening adjacent to water and transport of sheen into the marine environment.
- Action: The Ministry of Environment has requested copies of permits and storm water management plan from the Mill for review and immediate action to come into compliance with any permits / authorizations to discharge. MOE Compliance has been notified for further follow-up.
- General housekeeping @ Mill Docks recommendations made by Coast Guard

2018-0416  update from Ashley Robertson:
Flavelle Cedar Mill provided the following update which was shared with the City of Port Moody and Canadian Coast Guard:
"	No water processing occurs at site. No water discharge permits exists at the site. 
"	Flavelle has retained a qualified professional. Initial observations identify presence of wood extractives (natural wood oils) in storm water runoff and boomed timber in the inlet as a potential source of sheening.
"	Flavelle reports that immediate mitigation measures installed  sand filtration berms and hay bales. 
"	Runoff Characterization Plan and Storm Water Management Plan to be completed and shared with MOE upon completion.

MOE to update compliance. No further updates anticipated.

Location Description: Fish Processing Plants - Tofino & Campbell River *MEDIA
UA - Pitt Meadows Gun Club - eApprovals MO Request
18011 - Border Feedlot - Surrey - eApprovals MO Request
NRIS - Fish Processing Plants - West Coast
Inspection Summary:
On February 23, 2018, Officer Connor Fraleigh contacted Angela Koch to gather more information regarding her complaint. Ms. Koch indicated to Officer Fraleigh that she had concerns over the effluent discharge originating from Lion's Gate Fisheries Ltd. in Tofino, BC. 

Officer Fraleigh informed Ms. Koch that an officer conducted an inspection at Lion's Gate Fisheries Ltd. following the video that circulated online produced by Tavish Campbell. Mr. Fraleigh also indicated to Ms. Koch that samples were taken at the time of the inspection and that the results were currently available online. Ms. Koch raised concerns over the levels of Enterococci in the samples that were taken. Officer Fraleigh informed Ms. Koch that the Ministry's Monitoring Assessment and Stewardship team would be reviewing the data from those samples along with the samples being collected during the on-site inspection phase of the audit. 

Ms. Koch wanted to know why the Ministry was not halting each of the facilities operations until the results of this audit were completed. Officer Fraleigh informed Ms. Koch that without the audit results or effluent quality results from each site, there would not be sufficient information to warrant such actions against each facility. Ms. Koch acknowledged this but was still concerned over the facilities being authorized to discharge through another salmon run season. 

Ms. Koch also wanted to know what was being done with regards to the Piscine Orthoreovirus (PRV) across the industry. I indicated that there is still a lot of scientific review that is need to determine it's impact in British Columbia waters. In addition to this, I informed her that the Ministry does not regulate viruses related to aquaculture and that the Department of Fisheries and Oceans is primarily responsible for this. Ms. Koch was concerned that there is no requirements in our permits to require the disinfection of viruses. I indicated to Ms. Koch that the Ministry's Authorizations section would be completing a review of the audit results as well as reviewing each facilities permit to determine if any amendments were required to be protective of the environment. 

Ms. Koch was satisfied with the information provided but was not satisfied with the overall timeline for the completion of the audit. Officer Fraleigh went over the timelines and audit deliverables in an effort to explain that time is needed in order to conduct a thorough review of the industry. Ms. Koch acknowledged that there is a lot of work required to be collected. 

Officer Fraleigh then told Ms. Koch that if she had any additional questions, that she could reach out to either myself again, Glen Okrainetz (leading the Environmental Standards Branch review of the fish processing facility industry) or Karen Moores, Authorizations Section Head - General Industry.

Inspection Summary:
2018-02-20 SP searched on Waste Discharge Map KMZ Layer and did not find authorization at the business address. 

From altechcustomcoaters.com:
"providing the architectural and decorative finishes for aluminum and steel products"
ALODINE/CHROMATE CONVERSION COATING "Chromate conversion coating is a type of conversion coating applied to passivate aluminium, zinc, cadmium, copper, silver, magnesium, tin and their alloys to slow corrosion. Chromating is commonly used on zinc-plated parts to make them more durable. The chromate coating acts like a paint, protecting the zinc from white corrosion, this can make the part several times more durable depending on chromate layer thickness. It cannot be applied directly to steel or iron, and does not enhance zinc's cathodic protection of the underlying steel from brown corrosion."

"metal processing and metal products manufacturing industry" means establishments, except home-based businesses, educational facilities and establishments of hobbyists or artisans, engaged in manufacturing metal products that are also engaged in (a) spray coating or dip coating metal and metal products, or (b) galvanizing or electroplating;

2018-01-02 Contacted complainant via email 

2018-01-02 Contacted Tolko-Kelowna Manager Brent Rogers to inform of complaint and as him for reasons to cause the particulate discharge.

2018-01-05 Brent Rogers replied with information. He wrote: Hi Stewart. We did have 2 short duration issues on the weekend. One on Dec 29 for a few minutes upon start up of #1 boiler that was down due to metal jamming in a seal valve. The other was an electrical issue "loss of line synch" that occurred on Dec 31 at 0300 that took one of the 3 cells of the precipitator offline for a few minutes. The cause of this fault is being investigated. 
I can supply more detail, if you need some actual data please let me know. 
Brent"

Therefore it appears the causes fall under section 1.1.5 of PA-2082, which exempt opacity exceedances during startups and upset condition. for PM the only requirement for monitoring is the quarterly stack testing.

Section  2.2 Bypasses - The discharge of contaminants which have bypassed the authorized treatment works is prohibited unless the prior approval of the Director is obtained and confirmed in writing.
